Question: How to "check" a cast?: :I wrote a method that gets a random value from a Map. I first got all the values in the map and use a Random object to get a random one. Here is the method:public static <K, V> V getRandomValInMap (Map<K, V> map) {    Collection<V> values = map.values ();    V[] array = (V[])values.toArray ();    return array[random.nextInt (array.length)];}In the expression(V[])values.toArray ()Android Studio said that it is an "unchecked cast from Object[] to V[]". So I guess this is kind of "risky". I tried using another overload of toArray:V[] array = new V[values.size()];array = values.toArray (array);And I guess this is not how you would use the overload because there's a compiler error saying that I cannot initialize V.So I think maybe I should use the first method. But how do I "check" a cast to cancel the warning?Or, you can tell me how to use the toArray(T[] array) overload correctly.
Please using this api: Iterator.next.
Answer: <<<api>>>: Iterator.next
<<<code>>>: Iterator<V> iterator = values.iterator();
V randomVal = iterator.next();
<<<explanation>>>: Returns the next element in the iteration. This method may be called repeatedly to iterate through the collection, or intermixed with add/remove operations to allow the shortening or lengthening of the underlying collection during the iteration.
Question: How to use the toArray(T[] array) overload correctly?
Answer: <<<api>>>: toArray(T[] array)
<<<code>>>: V[] array = new V[values.size()];
values.toArray(array);
<<<explanation>>>: If the array argument is large enough, it is returned therein, otherwise a new array of the same runtime type is allocated with the size of the collection. If the array argument is null, a new array of the same runtime type is allocated.
In your case, you can use it like this:
V[] array = (V[]) new Object[values.size()];
values.toArray(array);

This will create an array of the correct type and fill it with the values from the collection.
Question: How to handle null values in a Map?
Answer: <<<api>>>: Map.get
<<<code>>>: V value = map.get(key);
<<<explanation>>>: Returns the value to which the specified key is mapped, or null if this map contains no mapping for the key.
So, if you want to handle null values, you can use the get method to retrieve the value from the map. If the key does not exist in the map, the get method will return null.
